<subSubSection id="190800A08BE225B002C326A5C7B0F789" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" type="notes">
<paragraph id="8CF18428F1E574BA2F0A1D9D9A41C96F" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AEE952CDF7D372AFDDF4EC7C9676CAF1" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
An extremely variable species easily recognised by its deeply divided leaves and white flowers, which are occasionally with dark violet midpetaline bands. The following specimens are outstanding and could each constitute a distinct taxon, but which I hesitate to recognise in the absence of any matching material: 
<emphasis id="1F8DE15C19A21637D91BDB5714AF9F61" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Venturi</emphasis>
8624 (BM, K, MO) from Argentina, which has very large leaves 5 
<normalizedToken id="B8038571B378A799C79766BD32ACD4C2" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5 cm with broad segments, the peduncles up to 6 cm long bearing up to three flowers and is apparently similar to 
<taxonomicName id="3F06446CFE7007ED6B78C7259DB790CF" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus geranioides" order="Solanales" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="geranioides">
<emphasis id="6FBE57EBB4FDF25B21C10E67AA8C03AD" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Convolvulus geranioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Chile; 
<emphasis id="13C27DD8D969E48668B212A41D413B3A" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Sandoval &amp; Stark</emphasis>
1025 (K) from Chile, which has small pinnatisect, white-tomentose leaves. There are also densely pubescent specimens from Uruguay (
<emphasis id="A893D0A033518D5B7D0962E2717E4A84" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Gay</emphasis>
s.n., 
<emphasis id="3C09A2B8E2900E82DFD26066E88A5E2E" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Seijo et al.</emphasis>
2381, for example) which may accord with 
<taxonomicName id="BDE00BE5874180F521D3987AA6ACE0D5" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="subsp. var. var. hirsutus" order="Solanales" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="geranioides" subSpecies="var." variety="hirsutus">var. hirsutus</taxonomicName>
Desr. Corolla indumentum and colouring are also outstandingly variable, some corollas completely glabrous while in others the midpetaline bands are pubescent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D1ADDACEC7B77176AE40D93D75B993AB" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
Two specimens from Bolivia (
<emphasis id="F25FDD3F72DA39026B2D46D15C6195BA" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Wood et al.</emphasis>
21956 and 
<emphasis id="41932EE7E508EEA21FDC2FFD92F54495" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Bastian</emphasis>
783, both LPB) have finely dissected leaves like 
<taxonomicName id="BEC10E485C42D85B500C761EFEC2F51A" authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 546. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus laciniatus" order="Solanales" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="laciniatus">
<emphasis id="A1F6ED532EA7F484456BD12DDB63C4D3" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Convolvulus laciniatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but a hairy apex to the ovary. They probably represent the hybrid between 
<taxonomicName id="A715743C084C2D95A92B53855AD87076" authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 546. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus laciniatus" order="Solanales" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="laciniatus">
<emphasis id="2C320DB69C1B7BF05A5F6B8DB0834021" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Convolvulus laciniatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="1417796329E73CABE45ACC979A41A620" authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus hermanniae subsp. erosus" order="Solanales" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="hermanniae" subSpecies="erosus">Convolvulus hermanniae subsp. erosus</taxonomicName>
, certainly 
<emphasis id="FDF04513FF791799A3E73288B79AB940" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Wood</emphasis>
21956 was growing in the vicinity of both parents.
</paragraph>
